description:
Transplanting
The very first big hurdle of the gardening season is transplanting. Transplanting is essential to the growth of plants and the consistency of your harvest. Transplanting is the process of moving fully germinated seeds or at times fully mature plants and replanting them in a permanent location throughout the growing season. Just remember that not every plant is suitable for transplanting and the back of the seed package will state which are not. These are best and more easily sown directly sown in the garden bed. Plants purchased at the garden center should not be allowed to remain in the pots in which you purchased them. Unless they are in a large enough pot suitable for growth. Most vegetables and herbs will need to be transplanted to provide an opportunity to grow and have space to develop a healthy root system. They can be either moved into a larger pot or into the garden bed.
There are several steps to follow to ensure success in transplanting. The most important thing to consider is the time of day and soil temperature. Springtime is usually the best time to transplant. Keep an eye on the forecast as planting too early in the season will weaken plants and even stunt growth if nighttime temperatures are too low. Plants are ready, about 2-3 weeks after plants sprout or when they have 1-2 sets of true leaves, for their permanent home. The time of day for best results are cool early mornings or late afternoons or on a cloudy day, since they will be allowed to get settled without direct sunlight.
Transplanting steps.
·       Ensure plants are sufficiently watered to avoid transplant shock and root damage. Roots loosen easier when the soil is moist.
·       Make sure to make a hole big enough for plants to go in.
·       Support the plants when pots are turned upside to remove seedlings to avoid stem breaking.
·       Put the seedling in the hole at the same depth as it was in the pot. Ensure the soil around root is level with the ground to avoid stem rot. Tomatoes however can be planted deeper since the roots grow along the vine.
·       Gently compact the soil around the plants and water immediately after transplanting
·       Once transplanted, plants may wilt or droop this is normal they will acclimate to the new environment after a few days. Keep soil moist during the upcoming days and never allow it to completely dry out. Water often until plants are well established.
Now that the plants are in their permanent home, take care of them for the rest of the growing season so you can reap the harvest of your labor.
Contact us if you have any questions at gardenevangelist@gmail.com
Happy transplanting!!
